The group of inventions relates to the field of medicine, specifically to orthopedics and traumatology, and discloses methods for applying antibacterial calcium phosphate coatings to orthopedic implants, particularly intramedullary fixators and pins. The method includes spraying a target in the plasma of a high-frequency discharge in a vacuum chamber of a magnetron sputtering system, in an argon atmosphere on an orthopedic implant placed in a fixture for a fixator or pin, on a rotary table in the vacuum chamber, wherein the target is made of zinc-substituted hydroxyapatite or copper-substituted hydroxyapatite. The coating is formed as follows:
- the vacuum chamber is evacuated to a residual pressure of (5±0.5)*10^-6 Torr, filled with argon, and evacuated to a working pressure of (8±0.5)*10^-4 Torr, followed by ion cleaning of the fixator or pin;
- a high-frequency magnetron discharge is ignited at a working pressure of (2±1)*10^-3 Torr at a power of 50 W, with subsequent stepwise intervals increasing the power by 50 W up to 250 W and maintaining each step for 10 minutes;
- the process of high-frequency magnetron sputtering is carried out by bringing the working vacuum to a value of (9±1)*10^-4 Torr, introducing the pin or fixator in the corresponding fixture into the magnetron zone, and maintaining this position for 240 or 380 minutes, respectively. The claimed methods enhance the antibacterial properties and/or increase the biocompatibility of the implant surface coatings, and also provide uniformity of coating application on orthopedic implants, specifically fixators or pins. 4 claims, 9 description paragraphs, 4 examples, 2 illustrations.
